<div id="review_3890768" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3890768" />
    <a title="Marc Horton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/242699-marc-horton"><img alt="Marc Horton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1192260292p2/242699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3890768?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marc Horton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marc Horton" href="/user/show/242699-marc-horton">Marc Horton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/242699-marc-horton?shelf=god-and-stuff">god-and-stuff</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3890768" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10075635671177491560">Obviously, anyone who can write a less-than-flattering book about Mother Teresa is not concerned with offending anyone. More or less, here&apos;s the rub: &quot;God&quot; explained a lot, back before we had Science and The Enlightenment, and now, humanity suffers at the hand of religious zealots whose battles spill over into the lives of the innocent. And one point that I&apos;m sure would make my mother cry: it is possible to live a moral and good life without &quot;God.&quot; Given the right subject, he&apos;s actually pretty f</span>
  <span id="freeText10075635671177491560" style="display:none">Obviously, anyone who can write a less-than-flattering book about Mother Teresa is not concerned with offending anyone. More or less, here's the rub: "God" explained a lot, back before we had Science and The Enlightenment, and now, humanity suffers at the hand of religious zealots whose battles spill over into the lives of the innocent. And one point that I'm sure would make my mother cry: it is possible to live a moral and good life without "God." Given the right subject, he's actually pretty funny, though he always dangerously treads the line between being obnoxiously and prodigiously smart. So, while I've disagreed with some his past books and ideas, this is one that fellow misanthropic humanists would do well to read. I'm reminded of a favorite Bill Hicks quote: "Humans? We're a virus with shoes." </span>
  <a data-text-id="10075635671177491560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
